"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388856","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-14","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to the hon. Member for Leicester South on 13 July 2015 to UIN 5983. An updated edition of the List of Ministerial Responsibilities will be published shortly.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2015-07-14T14:35:43.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388856/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388856/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-09","Ministers: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Ministers in which departments are special advisers in other departments; and what roles each such Minister holds.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","6314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388857","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-14","<p>I refer the hon. member to the answer given by my Rt Hon.Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office on 13 July.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-14T16:24:01.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388857/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388857/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Treasury: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the name, responsibilities and pay band are of each special adviser in his Department.","false","Biography information for Stuart Blair Donaldson","West Aberdeenshire and Kincardine","Stuart Blair Donaldson","6336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388858","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Digital Economy Centres were funded through the Research Council UK’s (RCUK) Digital Economy (DE) research programme. This theme has already invested over £170 million in applied multidisciplinary research across the Digital Economy - from societal challenges to technological solutions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Next Generation DE Centres will operate over a five-year period and will draw substantially on the knowledge and successes of previous RCUK Digital Economy investments. We have funded six centres and will continue to monitor the impact of the programme as these centres become operational.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There have been no ministerial or official level discussions with the Welsh Government on this issue. The Research Councils support academic research throughout the UK. The Centre based in Swansea is partnering with the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University NHS Trust and South Wales Police, amongst other partners.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The DE Centres were awarded as part of a peer reviewed competition during 2014/15. All applications were considered according to the RCUK standard peer review processes with research excellence as the primary criterion. <strong><em> </em></strong>Additional secondary assessment criteria such as evidence of co-creation with end-users, and clear plans to develop the UK Digital Economy community, were also considered. The Centres were also required to demonstrate how they would train skilled researchers and innovators.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","6399 ; 6470","2015-07-14T14:51:14.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388858/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388858/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-09","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, by what process his Department plans to bring forward proposals for the establishment of further next generation digital economy centres.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","6398"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388859","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Digital Economy Centres were funded through the Research Council UK’s (RCUK) Digital Economy (DE) research programme. This theme has already invested over £170 million in applied multidisciplinary research across the Digital Economy - from societal challenges to technological solutions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Next Generation DE Centres will operate over a five-year period and will draw substantially on the knowledge and successes of previous RCUK Digital Economy investments. We have funded six centres and will continue to monitor the impact of the programme as these centres become operational.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There have been no ministerial or official level discussions with the Welsh Government on this issue. The Research Councils support academic research throughout the UK. The Centre based in Swansea is partnering with the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University NHS Trust and South Wales Police, amongst other partners.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The DE Centres were awarded as part of a peer reviewed competition during 2014/15. All applications were considered according to the RCUK standard peer review processes with research excellence as the primary criterion. <strong><em> </em></strong>Additional secondary assessment criteria such as evidence of co-creation with end-users, and clear plans to develop the UK Digital Economy community, were also considered. The Centres were also required to demonstrate how they would train skilled researchers and innovators.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","6398 ; 6470","2015-07-14T14:51:14.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388859/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388859/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-09","Digital Technology: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with Ministers in the Welsh Government on the establishment of next generation digital economy centres in Wales.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","6399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388860","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-15","<p /> <p>The information is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate costs.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2015-07-15T12:22:28.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388860/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388860/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-09","Social Security Benefits: Ogmore","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in Ogmore constituency receive between £20,000 and £26,000 in benefit payments each year.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","6393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388861","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer has regular discussions with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on a wide range of topics.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is making changes to Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society. That means more emphasis on support to hardworking families on low incomes by reducing income tax through increases in the personal allowance and increasing wages, than on topping up low wages through tax credits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Parents currently on the minimum wage will benefit from the introduction of the National Living Wage from April 2016 which will be set at £7.20 per hour. The Government’s ambition is for the National Living Wage to reach over £9 by 2020. This would equate to a cash rise of £5,200 a year by 2020 for those who are currently working full time on the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","6402","2015-07-14T13:40:13.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388861/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388861/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the potential effect of the tax credit changes announced in the Summer Budget 2015 on families with two parents who work full-time on minimum wage with (a) two and (b) three or more children.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","6401"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388862","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-15","<p>HM Treasury does not require statutory provision to impose a financial penalty on a department. Rather, it is within the Treasury’s remit to set policy relating to public funds, for example the Civil Service Pay Guidance, a breach of which provides the authority to impose appropriate administrative sanctions at its discretion.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A financial penalty was imposed on the Information Commissioner’s Office of £18,400 for a breach of the Civil Service Pay Guidance relating to the salary increases of two Executive Team members. A statement was made publically in the Information Commissioner’s 2014/15 annual report.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2015-07-15T15:20:22.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388862/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388862/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Information Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 57 of the Information Commission's office's annual report 2014-15, under what statutory provision the Treasury imposes a financial penalty on that office; how the amount of that penalty was arrived at; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","6395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388863","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Chancellor of the Exchequer has regular discussions with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on a wide range of topics.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is making changes to Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society. That means more emphasis on support to hardworking families on low incomes by reducing income tax through increases in the personal allowance and increasing wages, than on topping up low wages through tax credits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Parents currently on the minimum wage will benefit from the introduction of the National Living Wage from April 2016 which will be set at £7.20 per hour. The Government’s ambition is for the National Living Wage to reach over £9 by 2020. This would equate to a cash rise of £5,200 a year by 2020 for those who are currently working full time on the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","6401","2015-07-14T13:40:14.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388863/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388863/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Welfare Tax Credits: Lone Parents","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the potential effect of the tax credit changes announced in Summer Budget 2015 on lone parent families in which the parent works full time on minimum wage with (a) two and (b) three or more children.","false","Biography information for Gavin Newlands","Paisley and Renfrewshire North","Gavin Newlands","6402"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388864","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-15","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2015-07-15T16:04:04.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388864/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388864/answer","PDF 6361.pdf","PDF 6361.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Earnings","UKSA Letter to Member - Earnings","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388864/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-09","Pay: Ogmore","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in Ogmore constituency earn between £3,850 and £6,420 annually.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","6361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388865","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-16","<p>This information is not available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Information about the number of benefitting families and average entitlement in the Ogmore constituency in the tax year 2013-14 can be found in the publication ‘Personal tax credits: Finalised award statistics – geographical statistics 2013-2014’ here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-tax-credits-finalised-award-statistics-geographical-statistics-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-tax-credits-finalised-award-statistics-geographical-statistics-2013-to-2014</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is making changes to Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society. That means more emphasis on support to hardworking families on low incomes by reducing income tax through increases in the personal allowance and increasing wages, than on topping up low wages through tax credits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>From April 2017, the child element of Child Tax Credit will be limited to two children. This means that families who have a third or subsequent child after April 2017 will not receive additional support for this child. Support provided to families who make a new claim to Universal Credit after this date will also be limited to two children. Equivalent changes will be made in housing benefit.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-07-16T16:09:10.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388865/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388865/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Social Security Benefits: Ogmore","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many families with more than two children in Ogmore constituency claim (a) child tax credits and (b) universal credit; if he will estimate the number of such families who will no longer be eligible to receive benefits for a child by the end of 2017; and if he will estimate the average amount by which the benefits received by such families will be reduced.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","6362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388866","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-14","<p>The information requested is not available. The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit (UC) in September 2013. As outlined in the strategy, officials are currently quality assuring data for UC therefore it is not yet possible to give a definitive list of what statistics will be provided in the future. These statistics however will be published in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for official statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The latest official experimental statistics on UC and the Departments release strategy can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","6417 ; 6463","2015-07-14T16:06:22.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388866/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388866/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-09","Universal Credit: Ogmore","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will estimate the number of 18 to 21 year olds in Ogmore constituency after April 2017 who will be unemployed and who will not be entitled to claim the housing element of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","6363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388867","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Chancellor strongly supports the Financing for Development Agenda, but the proximity to the Budget has meant he cannot attend in person.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for International Development is heading the UK’s delegation.</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-07-14T16:22:18.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388867/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388867/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","International Conference on Financing for Development","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will attend the Financing for Development summit in Addis Ababa from 13 to 16 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","6357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388868","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-17","<p>The Office for Budget Responsibility (OBR) forecast 1.1million new jobs will be created over the forecast period. This includes their estimate of the impact of the new living wage. This forecast is not broken down by region. The OBR also estimate the cost to businesses will only be 1 per cent, whilst Budget also announced a cut corporation tax to 18% and an increase in the Employment Allowance.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-17T13:12:58.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388868/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388868/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to his Budget Statement of 8 July 2015, Official Report, column 338, what estimate he has made of how many of the 60,000 jobs which the Office for Budget Responsibility estimates will be lost as a result of the introduction of the National Living Wage are based in each (a) sector and (b) region.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","6434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388869","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-16","<p /> <p>This Government is committed to working to eliminate child poverty and improving life chances for children.</p><p> </p><p>We know that work is the best route out of poverty, which is why we are focused on ensuring people have the skills and the opportunities to move into employment.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has carefully considered the impact of the tax and benefit reforms introduced in the Summer Budget. The intended impact of these reforms is to incentivise work, ensure work always pays, and then allow people to keep more of what they earn.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-16T15:11:24.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388869/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388869/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-09","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of measures announced in the Summer Budget 2015 on the level of child poverty among families who are (a) in and (b) out of work.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","6441"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388870","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-14","<p>The Digital Economy Centres were funded through the Research Council UK’s (RCUK) Digital Economy (DE) research programme. This theme has already invested over £170 million in applied multidisciplinary research across the Digital Economy - from societal challenges to technological solutions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Next Generation DE Centres will operate over a five-year period and will draw substantially on the knowledge and successes of previous RCUK Digital Economy investments. We have funded six centres and will continue to monitor the impact of the programme as these centres become operational.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>There have been no ministerial or official level discussions with the Welsh Government on this issue. The Research Councils support academic research throughout the UK. The Centre based in Swansea is partnering with the Abertawe Bro Morgannwg University NHS Trust and South Wales Police, amongst other partners.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The DE Centres were awarded as part of a peer reviewed competition during 2014/15. All applications were considered according to the RCUK standard peer review processes with research excellence as the primary criterion. <strong><em> </em></strong>Additional secondary assessment criteria such as evidence of co-creation with end-users, and clear plans to develop the UK Digital Economy community, were also considered. The Centres were also required to demonstrate how they would train skilled researchers and innovators.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","6398 ; 6399","2015-07-14T14:51:14.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388870/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388870/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-09","Digital Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what criteria were applied in selecting the next generation digital economy centres announced in the Summer Budget 2015.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","6470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388871","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-16","<p>The Government is making changes to Child Tax Credit and Universal Credit which will help put welfare spending on a more sustainable path. The Government wants to move from a low wage, high tax, high welfare society to a higher wage, lower tax, lower welfare society. That means more emphasis on support to hardworking families on low incomes by reducing income tax through increases in the personal allowance and increasing wages, than on topping up low wages through tax credits.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Families with someone working currently on the minimum wage will benefit from the introduction of the National Living Wage from April 2016 which will be set at £7.20 per hour. The Government’s ambition is for the National Living Wage to reach over £9 by 2020. This would equate to a cash rise of £5,200 a year by 2020 for those who are currently working full time on the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>These changes will ensure that work will always pay more than a life on benefits, support will be focused more on those on the very lowest incomes and the system will be fairer upon those who pay for it, as well as those who benefit from it. Taking the welfare changes in the Budget together with the record increases in the income tax personal allowance and the introduction of the new National Living Wage, 8 out of 10 working households will be better off by 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","6438 ; 6439 ; 6440","2015-07-16T16:40:29.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388871/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388871/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388871/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he plans to take to monitor the effects of changes to tax credits on families with very low incomes.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","6437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388872","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-16","<p /> <p>This Government is committed to working to eliminate child poverty and improving life chances for children.</p><p> </p><p>We know that work is the best route out of poverty, which is why we are focused on ensuring people have the skills and the opportunities to move into employment.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has carefully considered the impact of the tax and benefit reforms introduced in the Summer Budget. The intended impact of these reforms is to incentivise work, ensure work always pays, and then allow people to keep more of what they earn.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-16T15:18:29.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388872/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388872/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-09","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of measures announced in the Summer Budget 2015 on child poverty.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","6428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388873","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-15","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) regularly publishes general performance reports, including those for its Tax Credit Helpline, on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not record call waiting times on the HMRC helpline for Members of Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not have the numbers of staff employed to work on the tax credit helpline in the form requested, and it could only be collected at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>An average of 10-12 staff were employed on the HMRC helpline for Members of Parliament in each of the last 12 months.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","6488","2015-07-15T16:34:19.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388873/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388873/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-09","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the average call response time to calls made to the (a) tax credit helpline and (b) general HM Revenue and Customs helpline for hon. Members was in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mike Weir","Angus","Mike Weir","6487"
